<HEADLINE>
<P>
'BIG OIL' IS ALL OF US; 
</P>
<P>
A NATION OF GAS GUZZLERS CAN'T BLAME THE SUPPLIER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By COLMAN McCARTHY, Colman McCarthy writes a syndicated column in Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was lively theater -- but not much more -- when a member of Congress stood 
in the well of the House the other day and scissored in half his Exxon credit 
card. It was heady populism -- but not much more -- when some talk-radio 
babblers called for a boycott of Exxon. 
</P>
<P>
Aside from a few satisfying moments of stick-it-to-the-bums glee, these attacks 
on Exxon the oil spiller do little to protect the world from the next 
blackening, in Alaska or wherever. 
</P>
<P>
What does a boycott accomplish? Don't fill up at the Exxon gas station but 
drive down the street to Amoco? That's the company guilty of Europe's worst oil 
spill when its Amoco Cadiz came apart off the coast of Brittany in 1978. Or 
perhaps instead of Exxon, boycotters should buy from Unocal? It was 20 years 
ago this spring that one of Union Oil's offshore rigs broke and blackened the 
beaches of Santa Barbara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
I went to Santa Barbara in May, 1969, to write about the spill. Boycott fervor 
was in the air then, too. Union was vilified by a citizens' group, GOO (Get Oil 
Out). 
</P>
<P>
Big oil didn't get out -- not out of the Santa Barbara Channel, nor Prince 
William Sound, nor Antarctica's Palmer Peninsula where 250,000 gallons of oil 
were spilled last January. 
</P>
<P>
To be meaningful, a boycott of all oil companies would be needed. The 
congressman-showman who snipped his Exxon credit card would have been credible 
had he announced, say, that he was cutting in half his personal consumption of 
oil or was taking public transportation or commuting by bicycle to work or 
insulating his home, or was pushing for heat-tight buildings back in his home 
district where he rents office space. 
</P>
<P>
Energy conservation and energy efficiency is the only boycott that oil 
companies respect, because it's the only one that can last beyond the latest 
post-spill furor. If a nation's habits of consumption are radically changed, 
the oil industry's habits of production are forced to change also. 
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace magazine reports this month that "the United States loses more 
energy each year through poorly engineered windows than is provided by all the 
oil flowing through the Alaska pipeline." 
</P>
<P>
Environmental groups have deep wells of information to prove that America can 
save more oil than it can produce or import. The ability to change cars from 
gas guzzlers to gas sippers has been demonstrated. In 1973 automobile 
efficiency was an inefficient 14 miles per gallon. Two years later federal 
standards were passed and the efficiency doubled to 28 m.p.g. by 1987. The 
technology is available to increase it to 45 m.p.g. by 1995, which would 
eventually more than eliminate the need to import any oil at all. 
</P>
<P>
Nothing has been said by George Bush since the Alaska spill about rallying the 
country to conservation or efficiency. The former Texas oil man doesn't think 
that way. When he was vice president, Bush's Task Force on Regulatory Relief 
tried to repeal the 1975 fuel-efficiency standards. Congress refused, but did, 
as a compromise, weaken them. 
</P>
<P>
Instead of the President promoting conservation and efficiency, his Department 
of Interior is advancing proposals for exploiting coastal oil off Washington, 
Oregon and Florida, as well as in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge. Of seven 
industrial nations, the United States ranks last in the percentage of income 
devoted to energy-conservation research. 
</P>
<P>
If oil were an illegal drug, the United States would be the world's sorriest 
addict. It has 5% of the Earth's population but consumes 25% of its energy. 
</P>
<P>
The high from this addiction is so pleasurable that only a few politicians dare 
advance the conservation ethic. A member of Congress who called on Americans, 
let's say, to bicycle to work would be as ridiculed as Jimmy Carter was when he 
asked citizens to lower their thermostats. 
</P>
<P>
When freebasing, whether on crack or oil, addicts lose touch with reality. Now 
the Exxon addicts are announcing that they are changing dealers, as if becoming 
an Amoco addict is the answer. It's not. A boycott high, apparently, has some 
of the same thrill as an oil high. And the same downer after. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
