<HEADLINE>
<P>
'EYE ON L.A.' AND ITS SEGMENT ON CHILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
My husband and I have traveled in Chile twice in the last three years. Does 
that mean we are making (as it was put by Erik Nelson, former "Eye on L.A." 
producer) "a passive endorsement of what, at best, is a murky political 
situation"? Come on -- give me a break. 
</P>
<P>
LOUISE VAN DELL 
</P>
<P>
Corona del Mar 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051389-0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 56514 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 13, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part 5; Page 3; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
105 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
REVIEWING A LEGEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Using O'Day's age (almost 70) and her well-publicized personal problems against 
her is a cheap shot. 
</P>
<P>
Contrary to what Liska writes, O'Day was never known for her "bell-clear" 
instrument. She never had a voice and is famous for that fact. She is also 
famous for not having any vibrato because her uvula was accidentally cut during 
throat surgery when she was a child. 
</P>
<P>
She's the first to admit that she's not a singer. She's a song stylist renowned 
for her timing and interpretation, and for that reason she's considered one of 
the four or five most important vocalists of the century. 
</P>
<P>
ALAN EICHLER 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
